07342nam a22011175i 9783110705454DE-B159720220110023848.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220110t20212022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021942537  a97831107054547 a10.1515/97831107054542doi  a(DE-B1597)550935  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aREL0400302bisacsh00aNotions of Time in Deuterocanonical and Cognate Literature /ced. by Stefan Beyerle, Matthew Goff. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (XIV, 532 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDeuterocanonical and Cognate Literature Yearbook ,x1614-3361 ;v2020/20210 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA comprehensive investigation of notions of "time" in deuterocanonical and cognate literature, from the ancient Jewish up to the early Christian eras, requires further scholarship. The aim of this collection of articles is to contribute to a better understanding of "time" in deuterocanonical literature and pseudepigrapha, especially in Second Temple Judaism, and to provide criteria for concepts of time in wisdom literature, apocalypticism, Jewish and early Christian historiography and in Rabbinic religiosity.Essays in this volume, representing the proceedings of a conference of the "International Society for the Study of Deuterocanonical and Cognate Literature" in July 2019 at Greifswald, discuss concepts and terminologies of "time", stemming from novellas like the book of Tobit, from exhortations for the wise like Ben Sira, from an apocalyptic time table in 4 Ezra, the book of Giants or Daniel, and early Christian and Rabbinic compositions. The volume consists of four chapters that represent different approaches or hermeneutics of "time:" I. Axial Ages: The Construction of Time as "History", II. The Construction of Time: Particular Reifications, III. Terms of Time and Space, IV. The Construction of Apocalyptic Time. Scholars and students of ancient Jewish and Christian religious history will find in this volume orientation with regard to an important but multifaceted and sometimes disparate topic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 10. Jan 2022) 4aAntike. 4aHebräische Bibel. 4aJüdische Geschichte. 4aLiteratur des Zweiten Tempels. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh  aChristian Historiography.  aHebrew Bible.  amodels of time.1 aAbart, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBecker, Eve-Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeentjes, Pancratius C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeyerle, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeyerle, Stefan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBussino, Severino, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBöttrich, Christfried, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalduch-Benages, Núria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorley, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuggan, Michael W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEgger-Wenzel, Renate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFahl, Dieter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFahl, Sabine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoff, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoff, Matthew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJordaan, Pierre Johan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKepper, Martina, econtri